// Test: Doc-Mode Styling vs HTML
// Dieser Test vergleicht das Styling mit mirror-docu.html

// Globale Komponenten für Playground
Btn: pad 12 24 bg #2271c1 col white rad 8 cursor pointer
Card: ver bg #1A1A23 rad 12 pad 24
Tile: ver bg #3281d1 pad 20 rad 12 gap 8

doc
  text
    '$h1 Mirror

     $subtitle A description language for user interfaces.'

  text
    '$h2 What is Mirror

     $lead Mirror is a description language for user interfaces. One syntax for structure, styling, and interactions – that compiles to React.

     $p Building UI today means juggling three languages: HTML for structure, CSS for styling, JavaScript for behavior. Each lives in different files, follows different rules, and requires constant mental context-switching.

     $p Mirror takes a different approach. It is a single, declarative language where components, their appearance, and their behavior live together.'

  text
    '$h3 Learn Mirror in 2 Minutes

     $p Every example below is interactive. Edit the code and see the result instantly.

     $h4 1. A Component

     $p Everything in Mirror is a component. Every component has a name – this is how you reuse it later.'

  playground
    'Btn "Hello World"'

  text
    '$p `Btn` is the component name, `"Hello World"` is its content.

     $h4 2. Add Styling

     $p Properties style a component. Colors can be written directly without a property name.'

  playground
    'Row gap 12
       Btn "Short form"
       Btn bg #c12271 "Override"'

  text
    '$h4 3. Layouts and Children

     $p Components can contain other components. Indentation (2 spaces) defines hierarchy.'

  playground
    'Tile
       Label size 12 "Revenue"
       Value size 28 weight bold "2.7 Mio"'

  text
    '$h4 4. Reusable Templates

     $p Add `:` after a name to define a template.'

  playground
    'Dashboard grid 3 gap 16
       Tile Label "Revenue" Value "2.7 Mio"
       Tile Label "Customers" Value "40"
       Tile Label "Growth" Value "+12%"'
